Problem Definition

Virat is a working professional in IT Sector planning to buy a smartwatch to track his daily fitness activities and stay connected through notifications and calls. While browsing multiple e-commerce platforms, he finds hundreds of smartwatches with overlapping features such as heart-rate monitoring, Bluetooth calling, AMOLED displays, and fitness tracking.

Despite having similar features:

  • Some smartwatches are priced around 1,500 2,000

  • Others are priced as high as 10,000 25,000+

This large price variation creates confusion for Ravi and millions of buyers like him when deciding which smartwatch actually offers good value for money.

Business Questions

  • Is paying a higher price for a smartwatch actually worth it?
  • Do features like display type, Bluetooth calling, or fitness tracking significantly affect smartwatch prices?
  • Are higher customer ratings associated with higher-priced smartwatches?
  • Which smartwatch features genuinely increase the price?
  • Which smartwatches provide the best value for money in different price ranges?

Business Problem Statement

Smartwatch buyers face difficulty in choosing the right product due to too many options, inconsistent pricing, and unclear feature-to-price relationships. Many smartwatches offer similar specifications but differ significantly in price.

The goal of this project is to analyze smartwatch pricing and feature data using Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) to uncover pricing patterns, identify important features influencing price, and help consumers make data-driven purchasing decisions.

Project Objectives

The project follows a structured Data Analytics Life Cycle to ensure systematic analysis and meaningful insights.

  • Business Problem & Understanding Understanding the smartwatch market, customer needs, and pricing challenges faced by buyers.

  • Data Collection & Understanding Smartwatch data such as price, ratings, reviews, and product details is collected from Amazon using Selenium-based web scraping.

  • Data Preprocessing (Cleaning) Cleaning the dataset by removing sponsored listings, handling missing values, and converting prices and review counts into numerical formats.

  • Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) Analyzing price distributions, comparing brands, and studying relationships between price, ratings, and reviews.

  • Evaluation Evaluating whether higher prices are justified through customer ratings and popularity using analytical techniques.

def clean_reviews(value):
    if pd.isna(value):
        return None
    
    value = str(value).replace("(", "").replace(")", "").upper()
    
    if "K" in value:
        return float(value.replace("K", "")) * 1_000
    elif "L" in value:
        return float(value.replace("L", "")) * 100_000
    else:
        return float(value)

In[114]:
def normalize_os(os):
    if pd.isna(os):
        return "Unknown"
    
    os = os.lower()
    
    if "android wear" in os or "wear os" in os:
        return "Wear OS"
    elif "android" in os:
        return "Android"
    elif "watchos" in os or "ios" in os:
        return "WatchOS"
    elif "zepp" in os:
        return "Zepp OS"
    elif "pebble" in os:
        return "Pebble OS"
    else:
        return "Proprietary / Other"

Hypothesis Testing

EVALUATION (HYPOTHESIS TESTING) SMARTWATCH PROJECT

In[144]:
# Keep only valid numeric prices
df_test = eda_df.copy()

df_test = df_test[
    (df_test["Price"].notna()) &
    (df_test["Price"] > 0)
]

Hypothesis 1: Bluetooth Calling vs Price

EDA Observation

  • Smartwatches without Bluetooth calling showed a higher median price, driven by premium brands.

Hypotheses

  • H: Price distributions are the same for watches with and without Bluetooth calling

  • H: Price distributions differ significantly based on Bluetooth calling

  • Statistical Test

  • MannWhitney U test (Used because price is skewed with outliers)

In[145]:
from scipy.stats import mannwhitneyu

price_bt = df_test[df_test["Bluetooth_Calling"] == 1]["Price"]
price_no_bt = df_test[df_test["Bluetooth_Calling"] == 0]["Price"]

stat, p_value = mannwhitneyu(
    price_bt,
    price_no_bt,
    alternative="two-sided")

stat, p_value
Out[145]:
(np.float64(15349.0), np.float64(7.932239627284475e-22))

Result & Interpretation

  • Since p-value < 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis.
  • There is a statistically significant difference in smartwatch prices based on Bluetooth calling availability.

Business Insight

  • Bluetooth calling is common in mid-range mass-market devices, while premium brands often prioritize build quality, ecosystem, and brand value over this feature.

Hypothesis 2: Battery Life vs Price

EDA Observation

  • Battery life did not show a clear monotonic relationship with price.

Hypotheses

  • H: Battery life and price are not related

  • H: Battery life and price are related

Statistical Test

Spearman correlation (Non-linear, ordinal relationship)

In[146]:
from scipy.stats import spearmanr

corr, p_value = spearmanr(
    df_test["Battery_Life_Days"],
    df_test["Price"],
    nan_policy="omit")

corr, p_value
Out[146]:
(np.float64(0.03825805823892623), np.float64(0.38811916462679263))

Result & Interpretation

  • The Spearman correlation coefficient is close to zero ( -0.02) with a non-significant p-value (p = 0.636). Therefore, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. This indicates that battery life does not have a statistically significant monotonic relationship with smartwatch pricing.

Business Insight

  • Battery life alone does not justify higher pricing in smartwatches. Premium pricing is more strongly influenced by brand, ecosystem integration, and software capabilities rather than raw battery duration.
In[]:

FINAL BUSINESS INSIGHTS

Price Distribution Analysis What I Observed

  • Smartwatch prices are strongly right-skewed.
  • A small number of premium and luxury watches (30,0001,50,000+) significantly pull the average price upward.
  • Median prices are much lower than mean prices, indicating that most products lie in the affordable range.

Interpretation

  • The smartwatch market is dominated by budget and mid-range devices.
  • Mean price is misleading due to the presence of premium brands such as Apple, Garmin, and Samsung.
  • Median price better represents what a typical buyer actually pays.

Business Insight

  • Paying very high prices for a smartwatch is not the norm.Buyers should focus on median price ranges, not premium extremes that inflate averages without proportional everyday value.

Bluetooth Calling vs Price What I Observed

  • Watches without Bluetooth calling show a higher median price than those with Bluetooth calling.
  • Hypothesis testing (MannWhitney U test) confirms this difference is statistically significant (p 0.05).

Interpretation

  • Bluetooth calling is more common in mid-range mass-market devices.
  • Premium watches prioritize ecosystem integration, build quality, software, and brand positioning over Bluetooth calling.

Business Insight

  • Bluetooth calling is not a premium feature.Buyers should not assume that the presence of Bluetooth calling implies a higher-end or better smartwatch.

Battery Life vs Price

  • Battery life does not show a clear monotonic relationship with price.
  • Spearman correlation is near zero and not statistically significant.

Interpretation

  • Higher price does not guarantee longer battery life.
  • Premium watches often trade battery duration for advanced features, displays, and OS capabilities.

Business Insight

  • Buyers should not overpay expecting better battery life.
  • Battery performance depends more on OS optimization and usage patterns than price alone.

Price vs Reviews (Popularity Effect)

  • Review count shows no meaningful correlation with price.
  • Statistical testing confirms no significant relationship.

Interpretation

  • Review volume reflects sales volume and accessibility, not product value.
  • Budget and mid-range watches attract more buyers and therefore more reviews.

Business Insight

  • A smartwatch with fewer reviews is not necessarily inferior.

Brand-Level Pricing Differences

  • Certain brands consistently occupy higher price ranges.
  • Budget brands dominate the lower and mid-price segments, while a few brands form a premium cluster.

Interpretation

  • Brand positioning is a stronger price driver than individual features.
  • Pricing reflects ecosystem strength, trust, and long-term support, not just hardware specs.

Business Insight

  • Buyers should evaluate whether they are paying for brand value or actual feature utility.
  • For feature-focused buyers, mid-range brands often offer better value for money.

Outliers & Market Segmentation

  • High-price outliers are real products, not data errors.
  • These represent a luxury smartwatch segment.

Interpretation

  • The smartwatch market is segmented into:

Budget

Mid-range

Premium

Luxury

  • Outliers provide insight into market positioning, not noise.

Business Insight

  • Luxury smartwatches exist, but they are not value-optimized for most users.
  • Buyers should avoid expensive models unless they clearly benefit from brand ecosystem or specialized use cases.

FINAL BUSINESS INSIGHTS (Answering Buyers Questions)

  • Is paying more for a smartwatch really worth it?

Mostly NO. Beyond a certain price point, gains are marginal and driven by brand and ecosystem rather than utility.

  • Does Bluetooth calling justify higher price?

NO. It is more common in mid-range watches than premium ones.

  • Does longer battery life mean higher price?

NO. Battery life and price are largely independent.

  • Do more reviews mean better quality?

NO. Reviews reflect popularity, not premium value.

  • What matters most for pricing?

Brand positioning and ecosystem, not individual features.

FINAL RECOMMENDATIONS

  • For value-conscious smartwatch buyers:
  • Focus on mid-range price segments
  • Do not overpay for Bluetooth calling
  • Ignore luxury price outliers unless ecosystem matters
  • Choose battery life based on usage needs, not price
  • Evaluate brands carefully rather than chasing feature counts
